3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Funding rates on GMX are calculated hourly based on the difference between perpetual price and oracle spot price, with additional adjustments for pool skew and utilization. Long positions pay funding to shorts when rates are positive, with payments automatically deducted from collateral every hour. The oracle dependency means funding rates can diverge from pure market sentiment, as they incorporate Chainlink's aggregated spot price data rather than just perpetual trading activity."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","DOGE","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"DOGE/USDT on GMX attracts significant meme coin speculation, often creating pronounced funding rate imbalances during viral market cycles. The hourly settlement frequency provides more granular arbitrage opportunities compared to 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges, while GMX's unique liquidity pool model can amplify funding rates during periods of extreme directional bias."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"DOGE/USDT funding rates on GMX have historically spiked above 0.5% hourly (4,380% APR) during major meme coin rallies, particularly when social media trends drive retail speculation. During the 2023 Twitter rebrand period, funding rates remained elevated for 72+ consecutive hours as long interest dominated. The oracle-based model tends to create smoother rate transitions compared to order book exchanges, but can lag during rapid price movements. Base rates typically range from -0.01% to +0.05% hourly during normal market conditions."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between GMX and centralized platforms like Binance or OKX can be profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.02% hourly after accounting for transaction costs. GMX's oracle dependency creates temporal arbitrage opportunities when perpetual prices lag spot movements by 2-3 minutes during volatile periods. The hourly settlement creates 3x more frequent funding payments than traditional 8-hour cycles, allowing for compound arbitrage strategies. Traders often monitor GLP utilization metrics alongside funding rates to predict potential rate expansion."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Oracle Dependencies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's oracle-based pricing introduces counterparty risk through Chainlink feed delays or failures, particularly problematic during DOGE's characteristic volatility spikes. Price impact on large positions can be significant due to GLP pool depth limitations compared to major CEX order books. The 0.05%-0.07% trading fees can erode arbitrage profits on smaller rate differentials, requiring minimum 0.15% hourly funding spreads for profitability. Smart contract risk exists through potential GLP pool exploits or oracle manipulation, though GMX has maintained security since 2021 launch."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are DOGE/USDT funding payments settled on GMX?","answer":"GMX settles funding payments every hour for DOGE/USDT perpetuals, providing more frequent arbitrage opportunities than the standard 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges. Payments are automatically deducted from or added to your collateral balance."},{"question":"What makes GMX's DOGE funding rates different from centralized exchanges?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracle prices rather than perpetual mark prices for funding calculations, creating unique rate dynamics. The GLP liquidity pool model also means rates can be influenced by overall pool utilization and skew, not just directional trading sentiment."},{"question":"Can I predict DOGE funding rate changes on GMX using on-chain data?","answer":"Yes, monitoring GLP pool composition, open interest skew, and oracle price deviations can provide early signals for funding rate changes. GMX's transparent smart contracts allow real-time tracking of these metrics before official rate publications."},{"question":"What are the minimum position sizes for effective DOGE funding arbitrage on GMX?","answer":"Given GMX's 0.05%-0.07% trading fees, positions should typically exceed $10,000 to make arbitrage profitable on funding rate differentials below 0.2% hourly. Smaller positions work better when rate differentials exceed 0.5% hourly during meme coin volatility spikes."}]}]
